<section xml:id="sec-induction-intro">
  <title>Intro</title>

  <p>
    The <term> principle of mathematical induction </term>  is an important proof method in 
    most areas of mathematics. Before foramlly defining it we will illustrate
    with a simple example with two proofs using the same idea but different
    terminology. 
  </p>

  <p> 
 Formal defintions of these terms will come later. For now, simply aim to
 follow the various proofs of </p> 

 <fact xml:id="fact-3div4n-1">
  <statement>
    <p>
      For  <m>n = 0,1,2, \ldots</m>, 3 divides <m>4^n - 1</m>.
      That is <m>\frac{4^n - 1}{3}</m> is an integer.
    </p>
  </statement>
 </fact>

 

 <proof><title>Minimal counterexample proof of <xref ref="fact-3div4n-1"/> </title>

  <p>
    Assume that there is some integer for which the result does not hold.
    Let <m>k</m> be the smallest value for which <m>\frac{4^k - 1}{3}</m> is 
    <em>not </em> an integer. 
    </p>
    <p>
      Since <m>\frac{4^0 - 1}{3} = 0</m> is an integer, <m>k</m> is not 0. 
    </p>
    <p>
      Since <m>k</m> is smallest, <m>\frac{4^{k-1} - 1}{3}</m> is an integer.
      Then 
      <me>
        \frac{4^k - 1}{3} = \frac{4(4^{k-1} - 1) + 3}{3} 
        = 4 \, \frac{4^{k-1} - 1}{3} + 1
      </me>
      is an integer since <m>4, \frac{4^{n-1}-1}{3}</m>  and 1 are all integers. 
      This contradicts the assumption that <m>\frac{4^k - 1}{3}</m> is 
      <em>not </em> an integer. So there is no such <m>k</m> and the conclusion holds for all
      <m>n = 0,1,2, \ldots</m>. <m>\Box</m>
      
    </p>
 </proof>

 <proof><title>Induction proof of <xref ref="fact-3div4n-1"/> </title>


    <p>
      Since <m>\frac{4^0 - 1}{3} = 0</m> is an integer the claim holds for <m>n=0</m>. 
    </p>
    <p> For <m>n \geq 1</m>, by induction, we may assume that 
       <m>\frac{4^{n-1} - 1}{3}</m> is an integer.
      Then 
      <me>
        \frac{4^n - 1}{3} = \frac{4(4^{n-1} - 1) + 3}{3} 
        = 4 \, \frac{4^{n-1} - 1}{3} + 1
      </me>
      is an integer since <m>4, \frac{4^{n-1}-1}{3}</m>  and 1 are all integers. 
      Thus, by induction  the claim holds for all
      <m>n = 0,1,2, \ldots</m>. <m>\Box</m>
      
    </p>
 </proof>

 <p>
  In the induction proof the first sentence, establishing the claim directly 
  when <m>n=0</m> is called the <term>basis</term>. In general the basis will cover
  all initial  values for which the general argument does not work. </p>
  <p> In the second setence
  the assumption that the claim holds for <m>\frac{4^{n-1}-1}{3}</m> is called the
  <term>induction hypothesis</term>. In general the induction hypothesis allows us to 
    assume that the claim holds for all values less than <m>n</m>.
 </p>

 <p>
  Our purpose here was to start to illustrate induction. We can also
  give a short proof of <xref ref="fact-3div4n-1"/> using partial sums
  of geometric series as noted in <xref ref="rmk-geop"/>.
 </p>

 <p>
  We consider a toy problem called  Golomb's Tromino Theorem. 
  Consider tiling a <m>4 \times 4</m> chessboard with <m>L</m>-shaped
   <q>trominos</q>, 3 squares in the shape of an <m>L</m>.
 </p> 

