<p> 
Clearly we can't tile the entire board since each tromino has 3 tiles, so the total number of squares covered
must be a multiple of 3. However, we can cover 15 of the 16 squares. 
<xref ref="golomb1"/> shows two different tilings, each  missing one square. </p> 

<p> Can we choose any square to miss? It is not hard to see, for example, by rotating the upper right tromino, that
we can miss any of the 4 upper right squares. 
Then by rotating or flipping the entire board we can miss any preselected 
square. </p> 

<p> In general we can ask what kind of tilings are possible. Here, 
  to illustrate induction, we will
aim to tile <m>2^n \times 2^n</m> boards, missing any one preselected square.  There is at least a chance that this is possible
since we know from <xref ref="fact-3div4n-1"/>  that 3 divides <m>4^n-1</m>. Alternatively, our proof  that we can complete such tilings,
 which will not explicitly use the divisibility, will imply this division result as a corollary. </p>

<p> By rotating the large board, we may assume that the square missing a 
tile is in the upper right quadrant. </p> 

<p> Consider trying to tile an <m> 8 \times 8</m>  board with  the 
  missing the square in the top row, second from the right. Assuming that 
  we have already established tilings for <m>4 \times n</m> boards, we can 
  make an appropriate choice of four of these start to build a tilin gof the larger board.
  Then, by adding one more tromino we can complete the tiling of the larger board.
</p>
  
  <p> We  inductively
  use the board on the right in <xref ref="golomb1"/> and place this
   in the upper right <m> 4 \times 4 </m> subboard. 
   We then almost fill the remaining three
  <m>4 \times 4</m> subboards; lower left, lower right and upper left. Each will leave a missing square. 
  For the induction to work we need to line up the missing squares so that they can be covered by one more tromino.
  So we  put the missing squares for these <q>in the middle </q> of
   the large board. Each of these is a rotation of the board on the left in
   <xref ref="golomb1"/>. Then we complete the tilin gof te large board by
   adding one more tromino to cover the missing squares <q>in the center</q>.
  </p> 
  
