<p>
  We inductively used our smaller boards, each missing one square, placed so that 
one square  is in the right location for the  missing one in the larger square and the other 3 abut and form an
<m>L</m> that can be covered by one more tromino to complete the larger tiling. It should be
clear that we can continue this process to tile, for any <m>n</m>, 
<m>2^n \times 2^n</m> boards with any specified missing rectangle. </p>

<p> 
We will not write out the details. However this illustrates essence of 
proofs by induction.  We show a basis, in this case it would be the trivial
observation that we can tile <m>2 \times 2</m> boards with any missing square
using a single tromino. Then we can build to any size by using smaller 
boards, that we have already built, which we call the induction hypothesis. 
The description of how we do this building is called the induction step. 
</p>

<subsection>

 <p>  We have already seen an example of a proof by induction and a proof by
  minimal counterexample. We describe these more formally now. It may still be best 
  to not spend too much time of the formal definitions and instead jump to further examples that follow. 
 </p> 

  <fact xml:id="fact-wellorder">
  <title>Well ordering principle</title>
    
    <statement>
      <p>
        Every nonempty set of nonnegative integers has a smallest element.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </fact>

<p> This seem obvious and we will take it as such. Whether it is 
  considered an axiom or something proved from more basic axioms depends 
  on details of which system of arithmetic is being used. </p> 

<p> Despite its simplicity it is the basis a a fundamental proof technique. 
It is the principle underlying proofs by minimal counterexample. In these, we assume that the claimed result is false and consider 
a smallest counterexample. Then using the fact that for smaller examples 
the claim is valid, we reach a contradiction and then conclude that the 
claim is true.
</p> 

<p> The well Ordering Principle can be shown to be equivalent to the 
  Principle of Mathematical Induction, which we will state here. 
   We will skip a proof of the 
equivalence of well ordering and induction.
</p> 

<fact xml:id="fact-pinduction">
  <title>Principle of Mathematical Induction</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider a statement <m>P(n)</m> depending on integer <m>n</m>.  
      If for some <m>k</m>
        <ul>
          <li> <m>P(0), P(1), \ldots P(k)</m> are true (that is the statement is true for <m>k</m> initial values) </li>
          
          
          
          <li> For <m>n \gt k</m> truth is <m>P(0),P(1), \ldots, P(n-1)</m> implies the truth of <m>P(n)</m> </li> 
          
        </ul>
      
      Then <m>P(n)</m> is true for all integers <m>n = 0,1,2, \ldots</m>
    </p>
  </statement>
</fact>
	
	
<p> 
Technically what we just stated is called strong induction. Ordinary induction only assumes
a basis of <m>P(0)</m> being true and also only assumes the truth of <m>P(n-1)</m> in the second part. However these are equivalent. 
</p>

<remark>
  <p> For induction we can shift the <q>starting point</q> </p>
	
	<p> That is, if the statement is only true for values of <m>n</m> greater than some fixed <m>t</m>, we can start 
	with some initial values <m>P(t), P(t+1), \ldots, P(t+k)</m> and show that for <m>n \gt t+k</m> the truth
	of <m>P((k), \ldots P(n-1)</m> implies the truth of <m>P(n)</m>
	we get that the statement holds for all integers <m>k,k+1, \ldots</m>. </p>
</remark>

<remark>
  <p>
    The idea of mathematical induction is a common and extremely useful
tool in mathematical proofs. As noted,  it is essentially equivalent to proofs
based on the well ordering principle, 
where we assume that there is a counterexample and by looking at one
of minimum size reach a contradiction, showing that there is no
counterexample. In addition, induction is closely related to recursive 
algorithms. 
  </p>

  <p>
    Learning mathematical induction may be a bit like learning to ride a
bike. It seems almost impossible at first and you fall and scrape
your knees a few times but eventually you get it and it turns out
that it isn't hard and you can really do a lot once you figure it
out.
  </p>
</remark>

<example xml:id="expl-recurrence1">
  <p>Consider the recurrence <m>B_n =
    B_{n-1} + 6B_{n-2}</m> for <m>n \geq 2</m>  with initial conditions <m>B_0 = 1</m> and <m>B_1 = 8</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    This recurrence gives the sequence <m>1,8,14,62,146,518, \ldots</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    The
general formula is <m>B_n = 2 \cdot 3^n + (-1) (-2)^n</m>. 
 </p>

 <p>
  We will soon prove that the general formula is correct. 
 </p> 

<p>  If we have the formula, even without explanation or justification of how it was obtained, we can prove its correctness
using induction. 
</p>

<p> There are standard methods to discover these formulas. One approach, given without details:  Note that if a solution 
is for the form <m>x^n</m> for <m>x \not = 0</m>, then we have <m>x^n = x^{n-1} + 6x^{n-2} \Rightarrow x^2 - x - 6 = 0</m>.
A linear combination of the roots <m>-2,3</m> of this quadratic provides 
the solution with the multipliers <m>2</m> and <m>-1</m> chosen so that 
the initial conditions hold. </p>

<p> If the initial conditions change then the multipliers <m>2</m> and <m>-1</m> would change but the terms <m>3^n</m> and <m>(-2)^n</m> would 
remain. </p>

<p> Other recurrences of this form, linear, homogeneous with constant 
  coefficients have solutions in a similar way related to initial 
  conditions and roots of the corresponding characteristic polynomial. 
  This holds and produces real solutions even if the roots are complex. 
  The solution is a bit more complicated if there are repeated roots. 
  We will leave that for elsewhere. </p>

</example>

<p> We restate the formula from <xref ref="expl-recurrence1"/> and then 
give two proofs, with induction and minimal counterexamples for illustration.
The proofs are somewhat more wordy and detailed than necessary since these
are early examples. </p> 

<fact xml:id="fact-recurrence1">
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>B_n =
        B_{n-1} + 6B_{n-2}</m> for <m>n \geq 2</m>  with initial conditions <m>B_0 = 1</m> and <m>B_1 = 8</m>.
      then  <m>B_n = 2 \cdot 3^n + (-1) (-2)^n</m>. 
     </p>
  
  </statement>
</fact>

<proof><title>Minimal counterexample proof of <xref ref="fact-recurrence1"/>
   </title>
  <p>
    We prove that the formula is correct by contradiction.
Assume that the formula is false. Then there is some smallest non-negative
integer <m>n</m> for which it is false: the formula fails for <m>n</m> but holds for all smaller values.
That is, we assume that <m>B_n \not = 2 \cdot 3^n + (-1) (-2)^n</m>
but that <m>B_{n-1} = 2 \cdot 3^{n-2} + (-1) (-2)^{n-2}</m>,
<m>B_{n-2} = 2 \cdot 3^{n-3} + (-1) (-2)^{n-3}, \ldots, B_0 = 2 \cdot
3^{0} + (-1) (-2)^{0}</m>.  </p> <p> Note first that substituting <m>n = 0</m> and
<m>n=1</m> into the formula we get <m>B_0 = 2 \cdot 3^0 + (-1)(-2)^0 = 1</m>
and <m>B_1 = 2 \cdot 3^1 + (-1) (-2)^1 = 8</m>. So the formula works for
<m>n = 0, 1</m>. Thus <m>n \geq 2</m> and we can apply the recursion to <m>B_n</m>.
Using the recursion and the assumptions of the correctness of
the formulas for <m>B_{n-1}</m> and <m>B_{n-2}</m> and some basic algebra 
we get

<men xml:id ="eq-recurrence1"> 
  \begin{array}{rcl}
	B_n &amp; = &amp; B_{n-1} + 6 B_{n-2} \\
	&amp; = &amp; \left[ 2 \cdot 3^{n-1} + (-1) (-2)^{n-1} \right] +
	6 \left[ 2 \cdot 3^{n-2} + (-1) (-2)^{n-2} \right] \\
	&amp; = &amp; 2 \left(3 + 6 \right) 3^{n-2} + (-1) \left( -2 +
	6\right)(-2)^{n-2} \\
	&amp; = &amp; 2 \cdot 3^2 \cdot 3^{n-2} + (-1) \cdot (-2)^2 \cdot
	(-2)^{n-2} \\
	&amp; = &amp; 2 \cdot 3^n + (-1)(-2)^n
\end{array} 
</men>

Thus the formula holds for <m>n</m>, contradicting the assumption that
<m>n</m> is the smallest number for which the formula fails. So there
can be no such number: the formula holds for all <m>n = 0,1,2,
\ldots</m>. <m>\Box</m>
  </p>
</proof>

<p>
  The key to the proof was showing that if the formula is
correct for <m>B_{n-2}</m> and <m>B_{n-1}</m> then it is correct for <m>B_n</m>.
These are the equations <xref ref="eq-recurrence1"/> in the proof of 
<xref ref="fact-recurrence1"/>. Those computations
work for any choice of <m>n \geq 2</m>. So we could use them along with the easily
checked fact that the formula is correct for <m>B_0</m> and <m>B_1</m> to
show that it is correct for <m>B_2</m>. Then since it is correct for
<m>B_1</m> and <m>B_2</m> we use the computations above to see that the
formula is correct for <m>B_3</m>. Continuing this way we see that
we can build up to showing that the formula is correct for any
<m>B_n</m>.

We display this as follows:
</p>

<tabular>
  <row>
    <cell>Formula holds for <m>B_0</m> and <m>B_1</m></cell>
    <cell> <m>\Rightarrow </m></cell>
    <cell>Formula holds for <m>B_2</m>
    </cell>
  </row>
  <row>
    <cell>Formula holds for <m>B_1</m> and <m>B_2</m></cell>
    <cell> <m>\Rightarrow </m></cell>
    <cell>Formula holds for <m>B_3</m>
    </cell>
  </row>
  <row>
    <cell>Formula holds for <m>B_2</m> and <m>B_3</m></cell>
    <cell> <m>\Rightarrow </m></cell>
    <cell>Formula holds for <m>B_4</m>
    </cell>
  </row>
  <row>
    <cell><m>\vdots </m> </cell>
    <cell> <m>\vdots </m> </cell>
    <cell><m> \vdots </m> </cell>
  </row>
  <row>
    <cell>Formula holds for <m>B_{n-2}</m> and <m>B_{n-1}</m></cell>
    <cell> <m>\Rightarrow </m></cell>
    <cell>Formula holds for <m>B_n</m>
    </cell>
  </row>
